Solar Bilbao Port Authority awards contract for four solar plants Pamela Largue Aug 06, 2025 Share Image credit: Bilbao Port Authority The Bilbao Port Authority has awarded a contract for the installation of four solar PV projects, which will be incorporated in the Port’s Onshore Power Supply (OPS) system. The €11.4 million ($13 million) contract will see solar PV plants built within the Port service area, namely; in Zierbena Dock (809.6 kWp); on the Santurtzi breakwater (494.36 kWp); in the pre-boarding area of the ferry terminal at the A-6 Dock in Santurtzi (2,424.4 kWp); and in the car park at the Olatua cruise terminal in Getxo (527.12 kWp). The contract, which includes operations and maintenance, was awarded to a joint venture consisting of; Viuda de Sainz, S.L., Radimer Servicios Energéticos, S.L., Achiles Ingeniería Fotovoltaica, S.L. and Solar 360 de Repsol y Movistar, S.L.. The project must be completed within eighteen months. Have you read?Report predicts many US solar and wind projects won’t make itUK Power Networks uses AI to judge grid capacity from rooftop solar BilbOPS Project The installations form part of the Port’s BilbOPS project, which is designed to allow vessels to connect to the onshore power supply at the ro-ro, ro-pax, container and cruise terminals. BilbOPS combines power distribution and the production of renewable energy and will include 11 connection points with a power output of 30MW. The project is being funded by a grant secured from the Recovery and Resilience Facility, the Connecting Europe Facility (CEF) and by the Port Authority’s own resources. A loan of €80 million ($93 million) has also been secured through the European Investment Bank (EIB), part of which will be used to finance this project. Also of interest: How Valencia is decarbonising port operations with hydrogen According to the Port Authority, from 2027 onwards, the power to be supplied to vessels at berth will be of renewable origin, supplied by the distribution company contracted by the Port or by the Port’s own power production system. Sign up for our newsletter and stay informed Share Tags decarbonisation Previous Next #related-block_67712b6d707a07d5908c1e3146770662 .compact{background:rgb(245,245,245)!important;border:none !important;} Related Posts Negative power prices to increase as Europe’s solar output rises to record high Jul 11, 2025 New power purchase deal will see London’s Tube powered by solar Jul 05, 2025 New composite material to improve solar PV efficiency Jul 03, 2025 Australia launches floating solar research to boost drought resilience Jul 01, 2025 googletag.cmd.push(function () { var mapping = googletag.sizeMapping() .addSize([980, 500], [[300, 250], [336, 280]]) .addSize([640, 300], [300, 250]) .addSize([0, 0], [300, 250]) .build(); let adslot; adslot = '/' + gamAccount + '/' + sitePath; googletag.defineSlot(adslot, [[200,200],[300,250],[336,280]], 'side-block-top_block-advert-block_e36cd11b17bcb5f9fb97ab838964ea30') .defineSizeMapping(mapping) .setCollapseEmptyDiv(true) .setTargeting('pos', 'side-block-top') .setTargeting('page', 'home') .addService(googletag.pubads()); googletag.display('side-block-top_block-advert-block_e36cd11b17bcb5f9fb97ab838964ea30'); }); Trending this week{"title":"Trending this week","limit":"5","offset":0,"range":"last7days","time_quantity":"7","time_unit":"day","freshness":"1","order_by":"views","post_type":"post","pid":"","exclude":"","taxonomy":"category","term_id":"","author":"","shorten_title":{"active":false,"length":"25","words":false},"post-excerpt":{"active":false,"length":"75","keep_format":false,"words":false},"thumbnail":{"active":true,"width":0,"height":0,"build":"predefined","size":"plb-small"},"rating":false,"stats_tag":{"comment_count":false,"views":false,"author":false,"date":{"active":true,"format":"F j, Y"},"taxonomy":{"active":true,"name":"category"}},"markup":{"custom_html":true,"wpp-start":"","wpp-end":"","title-start":"","title-end":"","post-html":"

